description:
secretx-aws-kms/src/lib.rs:131-138 — 'fn fixed32(n: &[u8]) -> Result<[u8; 32], &'static str>' is defined inside ecdsa_der_to_raw_p256, called twice immediately after, then never referenced again. The function-in-function pattern is fine; using a closure would not change anything material here.

Mild idiom note: returning Result<[u8;32], &'static str> and then mapping the &str into a SecretError::Backend via .map_err(parse_err) is two-step error conversion. A more direct shape would be a closure that returns Result<[u8;32], SecretError> directly:
  let fixed32 = |n: &[u8]| -> Result<[u8; 32], SecretError> {
      if n.len() > 32 { return Err(parse_err("integer component exceeds 32 bytes for P-256")); }
      let mut out = [0u8; 32];
      out[32 - n.len()..].copy_from_slice(n);
      Ok(out)
  };

What goes wrong without it: nothing observable. Filed as opinion. Mark won't-fix if you prefer the explicit fn.
